**IS-LM-PC Teaching Tool — Master Plan**

*Consolidation + progressive-disclosure build plan · 18 June 2026*

# 1. Purpose

The full model (IS-LM-PC, Okun-modified, both closed and open economy) is built and equation-matched to Blanchard. The next phase is a teaching version that reveals the model progressively — every block stays visible, but blocks not yet taught are greyed out and locked. This document is the single plan for that phase and supersedes the older scattered roadmap docs.

# 2. Two design axes

Keeping these separate is what stops the tool drifting back toward 'demonstrate everything.'

- **Breadth (lesson level): **which blocks are live vs greyed-and-locked. The full model is always on screen so the learner sees where they are heading.

- **Depth (drill-down): **inside any live block, click a curve to expand its derivation — e.g. IS-LM unfolds into the IS relation + the LM-from-money-market construction. Available regardless of level.

# 3. Block structure (the onboarding sequence)

*Single progressive learning tool: one model that the learner unlocks block-by-block from closed short-run through to the full open-economy medium run. There is no longer a separate "free/closed" and "paid/open" product — see §7. The full model is always on screen; blocks not yet taught are greyed and locked.*

**Settled five-block order (confirmed by Frank): GOODS → ISLM → UIP → PC → DEBT.**

| **Block** | **Live (unlocked)** | **Free params** | **Blanchard anchor** | **Rate / inflation regime** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| **GOODS** | Keynesian cross (Y=Z) | G, T, c₁ | Ch. 3, eq. 3.6; multiplier 1/(1−c₁) | no interest rate yet |
| **ISLM** | + IS-LM chart, money market, policy rate | + i | Ch. 5; eq. 9.1 (IS) | **NOMINAL rate only: r = i.** Prices/inflation constant (Ch. 5 core short run). NO πᵉ control, NO Fisher line, NO real-rate line. |
| **UIP** | + imports/exports, UIP, exchange rate | + m₁, x₁, ε, Y*, i* | Ch. 18 (eq. 18.4); Ch. 19 (UIP eq. 19.5) | still nominal r = i (UIP is an open-economy IS extension, not the medium-run expansion) |
| **PC** | + Phillips curve, expectations, Yₙ, Okun | + α, z, θ, credibility, **πᵉ** | Ch. 8 (eq. 8.4–8.9); Ch. 9 | **NOMINAL→REAL distinction switches on: r = i − πᵉ.** Fisher line, real-rate line, and the πᵉ control all appear here together (medium-run/expectations expansion). Time-controls (Step/Reverse/Rebalance) also gate here. |
| **DEBT** | + government debt dynamics | + B, g | Ch. 22 (debt dynamics) | full model live |
| *(later) Forward FX (v2)* | + forward-looking FX expectations | + expected future ε | Ch. 20 (saddle path) | out of current scope per README |

**Critical engine consequence (DECISION OVERRIDE — supersedes earlier "πᵉ stays in ISLM"):** πᵉ unlocks WITH the PC block, not in ISLM. The ISLM (and UIP) stages are the Ch. 5 core short run using the nominal rate with r = i, where the nominal/real distinction does not yet exist. `solve()` must compute r = i when PC is locked and r = i − πᵉ when PC is unlocked, gated on tutorial state. This is an ENGINE change requiring a verifier assertion (output invariant to πᵉ when PC locked). To be run past Frank, as it reverses a previously locked call.

*Note on Frank's four-stage level progression (IS-LM closed → IS-LM-UIP open → IS-LM-PC closed → IS-LM-UIP-PC full): this still needs reconciling with the five-block sequence above. Open question: whether "IS-LM-PC closed" is a standalone unlockable stage or a transitional view. Tracked in §9.*

# 4. Open questions for Frank

The level-ordering question is now resolved: the five-block order GOODS → ISLM → UIP → PC → DEBT is settled (open economy before the PC, matching his Macro 2). Remaining open items for Frank are consolidated in §9 ("Still on Frank's desk") so they live in one place with current status — chiefly the πᵉ-with-PC override (item A), whether the GOODS block earns its place, the upward-sloping-LM drill-down, and the Okun/unemployment display.

# 5. Build phases

*These are the larger structural phases. The immediate, sequenced work is the queue in §9 (items A–D); Phase 1 below is partly that queue. Phases 2/4/5/6 are the wider frame to tackle once the queue clears.*

- **Phase 1 — Symbol tooltips + Blanchard references. **No engine changes. Inline hover definitions for every symbol within the equation boxes (§9 item C); inline eq. citations in the existing 'Show the equations' boxes (transcribe from the correspondence doc, don't re-derive).

- **Phase 2 — Lesson-level UI frame. **A top stepper bar above the charts. Decide visual style before deconstructing.

- **Phase 3 — Level system (grey + lock). **Config objects over the existing engine: which panels live, which sliders pinned. No economics changes, no engine forks.

- **Phase 4 — Drill-down derivations. **Click-to-expand views: IS construction, LM-from-money-market, PC-from-labour-market, Okun link.

- **Phase 5 — Per-level guidance. **Short intro + 2–3 guided scenarios per level, reusing the existing scenario system.

- **Phase 6 — Forward-looking FX (v2). **Genuinely new modelling (saddle path). Kept last and separate; out of current scope per README.

# 6. Consolidation status

Two folders drifted apart. The git repo (BLANCHARD MATCH FOLDER) is the live working tree, now committed; 'FINAL DOCS 0906' was the graveyard despite its name. Old model versions archived to _ARCHIVE_old_versions; superseded planning docs archived, with their useful ideas folded into this document.

# 7. Product framing & adoption

**The product is now a single progressive learning tool**, not a free/paid two-tier split. The earlier plan had a free closed-economy model and a paid open-economy model; that is superseded. The full model (closed → open, GOODS through DEBT) lives in one tool, revealed block-by-block via the onboarding layer. Any remaining "free tier / paid tier / v19 paid" language in the code (e.g. the Copy-state export header), the Correspondence doc, or the README is stale and tracked for cleanup in §9.

The adoption thinking below still holds, just without the tiered-pricing mechanics:

- **Individual lecturer / convenor is the realistic first adopter** — high autonomy, low budget. Frank using it in his own lectures is the single best adoption lever.
- **Department next** — a few people who know each other, modest teaching-resource budget.
- **University central / publishers are later, slower routes** — committee procurement, accessibility/security review; only worth it once the tool is proven in a real module.
- **Adoption inertia, not competitors, is the real enemy.** Lecturers reuse materials for years; a personal introduction beats any feature.
- **The realistic first loop:** one friendly adopter uses it with real students for a term → collect a short endorsement + student reaction → use that to approach the next two or three convenors. Turn the loop once and you have proof; out of scope to formalise pricing before the first yes.
- **Don't over-invest before the first yes** — tie development to actual adopter requests, not speculative features.

# 8. Document structure (avoid duplicates)

Planning/reference documents that should exist. Everything else is generated from these or archived. Update these in place — never make 'v2' / 'new' / 'final' copies; Git holds the history.

- **THIS master plan. **Goal, block structure, adoption, to-do. The doc you open and edit.

- **Model–Textbook Correspondence. **The equation-by-equation Blanchard mapping. Canonical, already in repo.

- **README. **For anyone (or any agent) opening the repo cold. Already in repo.

- **Onboarding_Build_Sequence.md. **The running log of onboarding slices built, in order, with their commits. Kept current as each slice lands.

- **Spec_Onboarding_StateMachine.md. **The live state-machine spec governing Slices 2–4. **Never archive while Slices 2–4 are open** — it is an active dependency, not a completed spec.

- **CLAUDE.md and .agents/AGENTS.md. **Always-loaded root rules. CLAUDE.md is for Claude; .agents/AGENTS.md carries the same standing rules for Antigravity (Gemini-based). Both must state the no-weakening-a-verifier rule and the spec-first/verifier-green gate.

*Applied specs are archived to _ARCHIVE_specs/ once their work is committed and verifier-green — EXCEPT Spec_Onboarding_StateMachine.md (live). Downstream OUTPUTS (instructor manual, tool one-pager) are remade from the canonical docs when needed — deliverables, not planning docs.*

